fctarbox3:
&lt;p&gt;I would propose that the half letters could be implemented through the
use of the shift key, i.e. &quot;Peep&quot; on the key &quot;p&quot; and &quot;half-peep&quot; on shift-&quot;p&quot;.&nbsp;
The half-letters, as I have used them being &quot;p&quot;, &quot;b&quot;, &quot;d&quot;, &quot;t&quot;, &quot;h&quot;, &quot;y&quot;,
&quot;w&quot;, &quot;hw&quot;, &quot;s&quot;, and&nbsp; &quot;z&quot;.&nbsp; All of these could be placed on their&nbsp;
standard qwerty key except for &quot;hw&quot;, which would have to go elsewhere.
&lt;p&gt;QS was designed to be easy to write in a connected manner without actual
connectors.&nbsp; That is, letters which can connect are permitted to,
and if they don&#39;t naturally connect, that is fine also.&nbsp; Many people
probably assume that QS in a printed or computer font would be written
as junior QS, i.e. with no letters connected to each other.&nbsp; However,
in my opinion, the natural ability of the letters to connect so gracefully
should be utilized, and with computer fonts this can be done.&nbsp; In
particular, the half keys are important for producing some of the most
distinctive word-shapes in QS.&nbsp; Other connections such as &quot;sp&quot; and
&quot;sk&quot;&nbsp; and the vowel connections to a following &quot;r&quot; are so natural
that is seems foolish not to use them when we have the technology to do
so.&nbsp; I do not believe that a computer font of senior QS is less legible
than junior QS.&nbsp; Does anyone here think that computer generated QS
should be left unconnected?
&lt;p&gt;I especially like the idea of the linkages being automated with a &quot;delinkage&quot;
key being available to the writer to enable him to modify such linkages
when it suits his pleasure.
&lt;p&gt;Paige G.
&lt;p&gt;fctarbox3 wrote:
&lt;blockquote TYPE=CITE&gt;&nbsp;&lt;tt&gt;Sorry for the extremely delayed response.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;Why do the half letters need their own separate keys?&nbsp; The
qwerty&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;keyboard has been pressed into service for writing Arabic, with&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;final, medial, initial, and isolated versions of most graphemes,
as&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;well as numerous vocalic diacritics; and Kana, where long key&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;sequences lead to single characters.&nbsp; This has forced the
advance of&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;font technology where the exact glyph used in a word can be&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;determined by the computer, not the author.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;Shouldn&#39;t a new font be taking advantage of this technology?&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;By being forced to write a rigorous set of rules for all the&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;linkages, we would also help disambiguate the precedence of the&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;different possible linkages, although this treads dangerously close&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;to reintroducing arbitrary &quot;orthodox&quot; spellings quickscript was&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;designed to avoid (instead of arbitrary spellings, however, they&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;would be more or less arbitrary &quot;graphings&quot;)&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;Should an author truly desire to force non-regular glyph-breaks,&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;this is facilitated by the addition of a null glyph; a key that&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;produces no visible text, but breaks up the characters so that
the&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;internal processor treats them separately.&nbsp; For example, st,&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;commonly joined along the top in quickscript, would display&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;differently from s.t, which would separate the two with no other&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;change in visible display.&nbsp; (The &#39;.&#39; would be a bad choice
for a&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;null glyph, but it makes for a very legible example)&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;--- In Read_Alphabet@yahoogroups.com, Andy Walker &lt;kyudosha@y...&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;wrote:&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; People have asked if I&#39;m going to take the&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; half-letters into account as well as wondering what&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; sort of &quot;layout&quot; I&#39;m talking about.&nbsp; I figure I&#39;ll&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; kill two birds with one stone, and show you the layout&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; I&#39;m currently using.&nbsp; Note: it is BASED upon a&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; one-to-one of the sounds represented by TO, but not&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; precisely on (as there are some letters that are&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; redundant).&nbsp; Where possible, I have used mnemonic&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; links to make things easier.&nbsp; Where not possible, I&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; have simply paired up a likely pair of characters on&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; one key (you will notice this with #39/#40.&nbsp; I have&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; ALWAYS tried to pair up characters in an intuitive way&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; on the keys.&nbsp; This is somewhat primitive (as I have&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; drawn the characters by hand in lieu of a finished&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; font), but hopefully you&#39;ll&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; see what I&#39;m getting at.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; NOTE: The dotted &quot;boxes&quot; represent that this character&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; is a half letter meant to be above or below some other letter.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;
&lt;br&gt;&nbsp;
